why is it happening i have a fish bowl gallon yesterday i bought a pair of red molli one was active the other seemed to be alone at the bottom of the bowl unfortunately today morning i found the inactive fish dead i don't know why it happened last week the same happened for an bronze gold why is one fish doing better and the other losing its life i feed them twice a day with dried worms and normal fish foods available in the shops please help me thanks a lot the root of your problem is that you have a small unfiltered bowl and when you add the fish ammonia accumulates overnight and kills at least one of them you need a filtered heated tank for fish like you want to keep i would suggest you check into a gallon started kit from a large petshop chain and also read up on what cycling a tank means and how to deal with it so you don't lose fish here's a link on starting up an aquarium that covers the basicas you need to know if after reading up you have other questions feel free to email me http www firsttankguide net mm Marine aquarium Aquarium Sea-Monkey Discus (fish) Brewery Biodiesel Poker jargon Autonomous building Vermicompost Sun Carburetor RuneScape quests Thermal power station Goldfish Sewage treatment Dairy Hydrogen economy Fish farming Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Pakistani cricket team in West Indies in 2005 Cyanide Bong GunBound Angling Fishing Dry cleaning Wheel of Fortune Tilapia Phishing Advance fee fraud Fish Gmail Cannabis cultivation Flush toilet E85 Animal Crossing The SpongeBob SquarePants Movie The Beatles discography Ammonia Seine (fishing) STS-59 Civil engineering and infrastructure repair in New Orleans after Hurricane Katrina Make money fast Clownfish SCO-Linux controversies Alcohol fuel Diseases of the honeybee OpenBSD Reef tank God Emperor of Dune Eutrophication Japanese tea ceremony E-mail XML Coffee Paul Is Dead Tlingit Omega-3 fatty acid The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time weapons and items RuneScape locations Shogi Opportu